          "body": "Verses 22-30 cover the conquest, settlement, and the long slow descent through the monarchy and prophets to the Babylonian exile. The conquest section (9:22-25) is deliberately maximalist: kingdoms given, Canaanites subdued, fortified cities captured, houses full of every good thing, vineyards, olive groves, fruit trees — 'so they ate, were filled and grew fat and reveled in Your great goodness' (9:25). The fattening is not celebrated; it is the setup for the devastation of verse 26: 'But they became disobedient and rebelled against You, and cast Your law behind their backs and killed Your prophets.' The image of casting the law behind their backs (*shalakh achar gav*, 9:26) is deliberately physical — the Torah is not forgotten but thrown, like an unwanted object. The Judges cycle is then compressed (9:27-28): oppression, crying out, compassion, deliverance, rest — and immediately the cycle restarts. Three times the cycle is named (9:27, 28, and implied in 9:29-30), each pass covering a wider era. The prophetic period closes the historical section (9:30): 'You bore with them for many years and admonished them by Your Spirit through Your prophets, yet they would not give ear. Therefore You gave them into the hand of the peoples of the lands.' The exile was patient discipline, not hot anger — which makes it, paradoxically, more sobering, not less."
